{{Infobox person | name = Aichatou Ousmane Issaka | image = Aichatou Ousmane Issaka IWOC 1.jpg | nationality = Nigerien | occupation = Deputy director of social work, military hospital of Niamey | awards = | honours = United Nations Military Gender Advocate of the Year Award (2016) International Women of Courage Award (2017) }}
Major '''Aichatou Ousmane Issaka''', deputy director of social work at the military hospital of [[Niamey]], is one of the first military women in [[Niger]]. In 2016 she received the [[United Nations Military Gender Advocate of the Year Award]] for her service in Gao, Mali with the [[United Nations peacekeeping]] force, [[United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali|MINUSMA]], during 2014-2015. She served as a captain in the civilian-military cooperation cell, training fellow officers and reaching out to local women, in accordance with principles of [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1325]] (2000) to increase participation of women and to integrate gender perspectives in peacekeeping efforts. Issaka also accompanied otherwise all-male patrols, making them more accessible to women and children. She was the first recipient of this award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/peacekeeping/issues/military/advocateaward.shtml|title=UN Military Gender Advocate of the Year Award|last=|first=|date=2016|website=United Nations Peacekeeping|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/apps/newsFr/storyF.asp?NewsID=38006#.WO7VsnrGpj9|title=Une capitaine nigérienne ayant servi au sein de la MINUSMA récompensée par l'ONU|last=|first=|date=September 7, 2016|website=Centre d'actualités de l'ONU|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nigerinter.com/2016/09/minusma-capitaine-aichatou-ousmane-issaka-une-nigerienne-recompensee/|title=MINUSMA : Capitaine Aichatou Ousmane Issaka, une nigérienne récompensée !|last=|first=|date=September 8, 2016|website=Niger Inter|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 12, 2017}}</ref>
On March 29, 2017, Issaka received the [[International Women of Courage Award]] for her peacekeeping contributions in Niger and in Mali, from [[First Lady of the United States]] [[Melania Trump]] and Under-Secretary of State for Political Affairs [[Thomas A. Shannon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/s/gwi/iwoc/2017/bio/index.htm|title=Biographies of the Finalists for the 2017 International Women of Courage Awards|last=|first=|date=2017|website=U.S. Department of State|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/s/gwi/iwoc/2017/index.htm|title=2017 International Women of Courage Award|last=|first=|date=2017|website=U.S. Department of State|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lesahel.org/index.php/component/k2/item/13865-le-commandant-aichatou-issaka-ousmane-laur%C3%A9ate-du-prix-du-courage-f%C3%A9minin-au-titre-de-lann%C3%A9e-2017--le-porte-flambeau-de-la-participation-de-la-femme-nig%C3%A9rienne-%C3%A0-la-restauration-de-la-paix|title=Le Commandant Aichatou Issaka Ousmane, lauréate du Prix du Courage Féminin au titre de l'année 2017 : Le porte-flambeau de la participation de la femme nigérienne à la restauration de la paix|date=2017|website=Le Sahel, Office National d'Edition et de Presse|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 12, 2017}}</ref>
