{{about|a criticism of chauvinistic attitudes within China toward ethnic minorities|the diplomatic system and ideology that emphasized China's centrality in the world|Sinocentrism}}
{{refimprove|date=April 2012}}
{{Chinese
|s=大汉族主义
|t=大漢族主義
|l=Great-Han-ism
|p=Dà Hànzú zhǔyì
|bpmf=ㄉㄚˋ ㄏㄢˋㄗㄨˊ ㄓㄨˇㄧˋ
}}

'''Han chauvinism''' is a term coined by [[Mao Zedong]] on March 16, 1953, to criticize [[ethnocentrism]] among the majority [[Han (people)|Han people]] of China. In a party directive drafted for the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|Central Committee]] of the [[Chinese Communist Party]] titled "Criticize Han [[Chauvinism]]" ([https://www.marxists.org/reference/archive/mao/selected-works/volume-5/mswv5_25.htm text]), Chairman Mao said, "In some places the relations between nationalities are far from normal. For Communists this is an intolerable situation. We must go to the root and criticize the Han chauvinist ideas which exist to a serious degree among many Party members and cadres&nbsp;..."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/reference/archive/mao/selected-works/volume-5/mswv5_25.htm|title=Criticize Han Chauvinism|last=Tse-tung|first=Mao|date=|website=www.marxists.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-23}}
</ref>

It appeared again in a 1956 speech, titled ''[[Ten Major Relationships|Ten Major Relations]]'', Mao stated that "on the relationship between the Han ethnicity and [[Ethnic minorities in China|minority ethnicities]]... we put the emphasis on opposing Han chauvinism".<ref>{{cite book| last = Li| first = Gucheng| title = A Glossary of Political Terms of The People's Republic of China | year = 1995| publisher = Chinese University Press | pages = 38–39| isbn  = 9789622016156}}</ref> This anti-chauvinistic idea is part of the [[People's Republic of China]]'s ''[[zhonghua minzu]]'' conception of China as a multi-ethnic [[nation]], both historically and in the present, which includes not only the Han but also 55 ethnic minorities. This is expressed in the [[constitution of the People's Republic of China]], which states that China is a "unitary [multiethnic] state created jointly by the people of all its ethnicities" and that "it is necessary to combat big [ethnic group] chauvinism, mainly Han chauvinism, and to combat local [ethnic] national[ist] chauvinism".<ref name="ghai">{{cite book| last = Ghai | first = Yash | title = Autonomy and Ethnicity: Negotiating Competing Claims in Multi-Ethnic States | year = 2000 | publisher = Cambridge University Press| page = 77| isbn  = 9780521786423}}</ref>

The PRC's notions of Han chauvinism and China as a multicultural state have been subject to criticism mainly from the western media. One critical view is that the Han Chinese "are less homogeneous than official policy recognizes".<ref name="ghai"/> Zhonghua minzu has been criticized as an invention of the 20th century, and was adopted by the Communist Party only to criticize the failures of the rival [[Kuomintang]], which officially promoted zhonghua minzu as part of its nationalist ideology. Many policies are made to give privilege to minority ethnicity, causing grudges from the Han Chinese.<ref name="liu">{{cite book| last = Liu | first = Xiaoyuan | title = Recast All Under Heaven: Revolution, War, Diplomacy, and Frontier China in the 20th Century | year = 2010 | publisher = Recast All Under Heaven: Revolution, War, Diplomacy, and Frontier China in the 20th Century | pages = 115–116| isbn  = 9781441134899}}</ref> This is comparable to reactions to [[affirmative action in the United States]], particularly allegations of {{Section link|Affirmative action in the United States|Reverse discrimination|nopage=y}}.

