{{for|issues related to the Irish border and Brexit|Irish border question}}
{{More citations needed|date=February 2013}}
[[Image:Map of Ireland's capitals.png|thumb|A political map of Ireland]]
The '''Irish Question''' was a phrase used mainly by members of the British ruling classes from the early 19th century until the 1920s. It was used to describe [[Irish nationalism]] and the calls for [[Irish republicanism|Irish independence]].

For the political history see [[Irish issue in British politics]]

The phrase came to prominence as a result of the 1800 [[Act of Union 1800|Act of Union]] which forced the parliament of [[Ireland]] into a single governing body with the parliament of [[Great Britain]], based in Westminster, with its usage persisting until the signing of the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]] in 1921, which partitioned the island into two territories: a state now called [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] (which was originally called the [[Irish Free State]]), and [[Northern Ireland]], which remains part of the [[United Kingdom]].

In 1844, a future British prime minister, [[Benjamin Disraeli]], defined the Irish Question:
{{quote|A dense population, in extreme distress, inhabit an island where there is an Established Church, which is not their Church, and a territorial aristocracy the richest of whom live in foreign capitals. Thus you have a starving population, an absentee aristocracy, and an alien Church; and in addition the weakest executive in the world. That is the Irish Question.'|Hansard<ref>The State of Ireland,  Hansard, 16 February 1844</ref>}}

In 1886, with the introduction of the first Home Rule Bill in the House of Commons, the term 'the Anglo-Irish Quarrel'<ref>''The Anglo-Irish Quarrel: A Plea for Peace'', John O'Connor Power, London, 1886</ref> gained favour and  became more acceptable than the implied condescension of 'the Irish Question'.

Issues relating to Northern Ireland since the 1920s are often referred to as either "[[The Troubles]]" or "[[The Irish Problem]]".

The Irish question affected British politics much the way that the nationalities problem affected Austria. Normal British domestic issues could not be adequately addressed because of the political divisions created by the oppression of Ireland. The split of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] hurt the cause of further social and political reform. The people who could agree about reforms could not agree on Ireland, and Ireland seemed more important. Because the two traditional parties failed to deal with the social questions, by the turn of the 20th century a newly organised [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] began to fill the vacuum.

In 2017, the term was also used to describe issues associated with the [[Republic of Ireland–United Kingdom border#brexit|UK-Irish border]] and [[Brexit]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Toynbee|first1=Polly|title=The Irish question may yet save Britain from Brexit {{!}} Polly Toynbee|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/nov/27/irish-question-save-britain-brexit-leo-varadkar|work=The Guardian|date=27 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-41689168|title=Brexit viewed from Brussels: The Irish question}}</ref>

